<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n43097c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n43" href="#n43097c">N43 (VI.B.35)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n43all.htm#n43097c"> 97(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pantli nochtli / ametyl / flagstone peastone / water aloe</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Account of the attempts of post-<i>Conquest</i> Spanish &ldquo;missionaries&rdquo; to have prayers translated by using Aztec ideograms]</font> <i>Pater noster</i> was written by a flag (<i>pantli</i>) and a prickly pear (<i>nochtli</i>), while the sign of water, <i>a&nbsp;(tl)</i>, combined with that of aloe, <i>me&nbsp;(tl)</i>, made a compound word <i>ametyl</i>, which would mean &ldquo;water-aloe&rdquo;, but in sound made a very tolerable substitute for Amen. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECSA2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECSA2"><cite title="source">The Story of the Alphabet</cite></a>, rev. ed. (1913) 80 [Memory-aids and Picture-writing]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
